description.value: Round bottomed bowl, sheet brass engraved and inlaid with silver, gold and black organic inlay. Around the outside of the bowl is an inscription frieze interrupted six times by a vertical band of laced quatrefoils. These are filled with geometric patterns inlaid in silver with small dots of gold. Below the inscription is a narrow border of foliate scroll interrupted by six 8-petalled rosettes. The rim is decorated with a feather motif on the side; the top of the rim appears to have been engraved and possibly inlaid with a leafy scroll interrupted by twelve 5-petalled rosettes. The base is decorated with a large roundel containing a design based on six intersecting circles, which have been elaborated with lobes. description.value: Hemispherical laced glass bowl; colourless with translucent yellow threads and translucent brown rim; rounded rim; hemispherical body; convex base; body formed by a pair of coils made from twisted canes of bichrome glass wound spirally from the centre of the base to below the rim; each cane was made by drawing out and twisting a double gather of colourless glass and yellowish glass; the coils were laid side by side but with their thread decorations in opposite directions, thus forming a chevron pattern; rim formed by applying a translucent brown coil; traces of rotary polishing on interior and exterior; rim carefully rounded by grinding; either slumped over a convex former and possibly covered with an outer mould and fused through reheating, or alternatively possibly by heating and coiling canes around a bowl-shaped mould as it was turned on a turntable; then finished by grinding and polishing.

description.value: Faience three footed bowl of simple hemispherical shape, with three projections jutting from near its base to hold it steady. Three kneeling figures face outward, modelled in the round. They kneel on the flat surfaces of the feet-like props of the bowl, all wearing a garment to the knee, which has pleats indicated by vertical grooves. The figures are bare-chested and each has a beard and hair falling onto the shoulders coloured in black-brown glaze.  On the surface of the bowl there are also two lions and an ibex in low relief. The lions have dots along their tails and legs and several longer stripes on body. The ibex is depicted in a conventional galloping way, moving to right. It has dots on legs, in rows along back, on neck and along the horn.  There is also a large rosette in low relief slightly raised above the surface at the centre of exterior base between feet. It has seventeen petals, unequally divided by broad incised lines. The centre of the flower is represented by a circular cross-hatched area, with a central dot of more black-brown glaze.

description.value: Deep silver bowl and cover, cast; parcel gilt, both richly decorated with designs in relief. The bowl is of squat form bulging near the bottom; the lip is moulded. The ornament on the outside of the bowl forms a regular pattern, in which four large panels are separated at equal intervals by vine-scrolls. Within each panel is a large quatrefoil having in the middle a cross pattee with rosette centre and leaves between the arms. The vine-branches spring scrollwise from the leaves of the quatrefoils; each encloses a bird looking backwards and pecking at a conventional bunch of grapes: the spandrels are occupied by acanthus-leaves. The stems at their point of contact are bound by collar-like transverse bands, and form in the centre of the pattern lozenges with incurved sides enclosing small quatrefoils: the figures of the birds, the clusters of grapes, and the leaves are nielloed. The bottom has been rasped or filed. The cover is slightly convex, and has a beaded edge and a vertical handle, on the top of which is a nielloed quatrefoil with a rosette in the centre. The ornament on the cover is essentially the same as that on the bowl but on a smaller scale, and is similarly nielloed, but has no figures of birds. The background and interior of bowl and cover are gilt.

description.value: Rusty grey, slightly bent, rectangular metal cigarette box with a lid and part of the paper label. One side of the box is now open. The lid was originally hinged, however, the hinges are now broken off the box. The paper label on the lid is very colourful with a depiction of a bare-breasted woman smoking a cigarette. She is surrounded by mounds of fabric or cushions and wears a gold coloured necklace and headveil with gold coins along the edge. Pharaonic style columns and a cornice are visible in the background on the left side. The box is originally from Cairo. The labels on the sides show palm trees while the ones on the end advertise the product (100 cigarettes, format petit), its origin (Cairo, Egypt) and manufacturer (Aravanopoulos & Cie)

description.value: God cuff bracelet of Prince Nemareth: the inner side of the smaller segment of this bracelet is inscribed for a man with the Libyan name of Nimlot (also rendered as Nemareth or the like). The external decoration of the bracelet consists of geometric decoration and a figure of a child god. The god is represented in a typical ancient Egyptian manner for a male child: nude, wearing a long sidelock of hair and with a finger to the mouth. That this is not a mere human child, however, is indicated by his crook-shaped scepter of rule, the uraeus on his forehead, and his headdress, which is a lunar crescent and disk.
